< review>
By far one of the roomiest Starbucks location in the county. This was a former Burger King so the amount of space that is a commodity in other Starbucks locations is plentiful here. Been here twice, one mobile order and one walk in order, and I've had pleaseant experiences both times. Would recommend this place in a heartbeat if you want a sit down area to study.</review>

Thank you for continuing to provide an incredibly valuable service to make each day just a bit easier.</review>

< Review>
Know what you're getting into so you can appreciate it for what it is - a luxury advanced hot yoga studio. All of the elements are advanced. The dark room makes it difficult to balance, it's heated, fast-paced, and most poses come with levels 1-4 for difficulty. This place is great for advancing your practice and getting a great work out in. My first class was a shock to the system, but by the end of my new member trial, I was raving to all of my friends about it.<//Review>

< review>
I became a dedicated yoga student, thanks to  Yoga House, in 2009 during a very difficult period of my life and as a result experienced healing, well being, and greater contentment. Because of my physical, psychological, and soul-enriching experience at Yoga House, the studio remains a sacred space for me.

In 2017, I began taking Hannah Kapp‚Äôs classes every Monday and Thursday. She is an amazing teacher committed to creating a healing experience through asana, mudra, mantra, and music. She weaves in chanting and on occasion her talented singing and harp playing. I‚Äôm grateful for the devotion and dedication apparent in her asana sequencing and for her passion for yoga philosophy and healing all on levels.

Jill is another amazing and gifted teacher. This past week I took her gentle yoga class. She greets students with enthusiasm and kindness and skillfully leads the class through revitalizing poses and stretches. I left feeling seen, respected, and renewed.

In sum, Yoga House is an awesome studio that remains an essential place for me in Pasadena. A deep and sincere thank you to the Yoga House owner, staff, and teachers for improving the quality of my heart, health, and spirit over the past decade. I‚Äôm grateful for all that you do!<//review>

We were rudely ignored and long story short, received the WORST customer service by their very own manager, MARILYN. <Pics>None</Pics><Rate>5< /Rate>< text>
When deciding to refinance my home to a lower rate, I decided to go with Ladera Lending, which was referred by Lending Tree.  They responded quickly and offered a great rate.  The only concern for me was that this was the first time I had done a transaction of this size without a face to face meeting with the people I would be working with, and that made me a little nervous.  Turning over all my personal and credit information including SSN and bank account numbers was unnerving.  The slightest delay in reaching the team at Ladera (led in my case by Sebastian Stalker) brought concerns that I had walked into a scam.

My worry was misplaced and that was reinforced every time I reached out to them.  Sebastian or an appropriate team member would quickly reply with the requested information and a few words to sooth my nerves.  I was also impressed by the professional companies that were employed by Ladera to complete the on site requirements for the transaction.

In the end, I got a fantastic rate, a quick and fair process, and easy to follow steps to that got me across the finish line. At the beginning Sebastian laid out a plan and time line and Ladera held to it, mark me as impressed.

I would NOT hesitate to use them again, except that my rate is so low it has nowhere to go but up.</text>

Franklin Lynch< /user_name>
<Time>1551286366917< /Time><Rating>1<//Rating>< Text>
I see that several people had positive experiences with Ladera Lending. My experience was on the opposite end of the spectrum. I have been told that we were at the finish line and ready to close since December. Initially my rep was responsive and on the ball. As we moved through the process I was told that they needed 1 or 2 more items to close several times. Each time I submitted what was asked for within hours and didn't receive any reply for days. I would have to call for updates and at times still took days to get back to me. It is a frustrating experience to say the least. Finally they came back with stipulations that made no sense for what was happening with the home. The loan was to do home improvements, and a s stipulations to fund they wanted a wall that was set to be removed to be painted, and for carpet to be laid in rooms that we're set to be sanded and painted. I turned in the work order to show that all of this work was set to be completed but it made no sense to spend money to complete things that would have to be removed as soon as the loan was funded. They also asked that I pay for a 2nd opinion on the appraisal. They we're the ones who chose the initial appraiser so if they don't trust his appraisal after I was forced to spend $500 with who they selected I shouldn't be on the hook for a 2nd opinion. In closing I was told if I did XYZ that we could move forward with closocl several times. The final straw was the redundant repairs that they wanted completed before funding, and requiring me to pay for a 2nd opinion on an appraisal that they selected the appraiser. I refused to spend more money because for 2 months I was promised a closing that never happened and there was no garunrtee on a closing date even if I did complete these steps. I feel like I wasted time and money and I wish that I would have went with another lender out of the gate, because now I am back at square 1 having to start the process all over again with a new lender.< /Text>

We just completed our refinance withe Ladera Lending.  Tommy Osborne, of Ladera Lending handled the refinance.  Tommy was very knowledgeable and and extreme pleasure to work with.  One of the best things about working with Tommy was his consistent communication with us during the process. I don't mean just e-mails, I mean real "old fashioned" personal conversation with us by phone. This way we were able to give and receive information in real discussion.  He answered all our questions fully and in ways that we could clearly understand, and made us fee that he was there to help us get through our refinancing timely and efficiently.
Whatever he said he would do, he followed through every time.

I have always referred to mortgage financing as "financing Hell".  In this case Tommy Osborne and Ladera Lending made our refinancing a pleasurable experience, and demonstrated that mortgage lending does not have to be a "torturous event".

Thank you again and again Tommy Osborne and Ladera Lending. We really appreciate your great work.  If every person at Ladera Lending is as courteous and professional as Tommy, is is not surprising that your company success as a mortgage lender thrives and should continue to do so.

<user_name>Tom Dauphin</user_name>< review>
Just a short note to say what a great experience it was to refinance our adjustable rate mortgage to a fixed rate and shortening its length to 15 years. This was all done from the comfort of my easy chair and computer terminal at our home here in Glendale, AZ thanks to Patrick Creavy. He kept us informed at every step of the way and managed to expediently fix the few glitches we experienced at title closing. <review>When I decided to refinance the house, I jumped on line and entered my information, including the fact I'm a vet,  into a mortgage information provider. They said they would forward my information to 5 lenders. Ha! Try 20. However, it was well worth the aggravation of dealing with all those phone calls and emails, because in the end I found Patrick Creavy of Ladera Lending.

A couple of the lenders offered decent interest rates and plenty of information. Fortunately, Patrick came on board before I actually signed with one of them. The other two lenders told me the VA funding fee was a waste of money. Patrick explained the Interest Rate Reduction Refinance Loan (IRRRL) program associated with the VA. If, at any point, interest rates fall, a vet can apply for an IRRRL. No appraisal, no title fees, no income verification. It's just a lowering of the rate. I was furious at first. I had purchased my home with a VA loan initially. I had refinanced 3 times for the sole purpose of lowering the interest rate. Every one of those financial institutes had talked me out of VA. The initial refinance had not told me about IRRRL. Why would they? Less money in their pocket. When I expressed this to Patrick, he assured me it wasn't deliberate. Most lenders do not specialize in VA, and are therefore ignorant of the benefits. Their ignorance cost me more than $28,000.

Patrick is friendly, honest, and knowledgeable. He believes in communication, and kept me abreast during the entire process. I  am amazed by the quality of his customer service; he's one in a million. I now consider him my personal loan advisor. I have been distributing his cards to friends and family. Need I say more?I would recommend him to anyone, but especially to veterans.<//review><Pics>None<//Pics>< Rating>

< Text>
I was referred to Chris Coble by another party who contacted me to see if I was interested in refinancing my home.  I was not in the market for refinancing options because we plan on selling our house within the next two years and plus I didn‚Äôt want to reduce the equity we had in the house and pay less on principle each month.  So let‚Äôs just say I wasn‚Äôt very interested in talking about refinancing at all‚Ä¶ well that was until I spoke to Chris.  I mentioned the above concerns to Chris and he understood my concerns and told me that he could save me $200-$400 a month on my mortgage payment.   While not decreasing the equity in my home significantly by utilizing the VA refinancing options, and there is a possibility we wouldn‚Äôt have to make payments for the first two months.  Chris volunteered to send me some numbers that reflected our conversation, I also did my own mortgage amortization calculations and came up with very similar numbers.  At that point I decided to do move forward with VA refinancing option, thanks to Chris.  I‚Äôm a hard person to convince and live by the motto DTA (Don‚Äôt Trust Anyone).  So for Chris to get me to trust him in getting us the best rate and options for our mortgage is a testament to him and his dedication to his profession.

So, then begins the process of submitting documents and filling out applications.  Compared to our first mortgage process this one was very streamlined and a majority of it was completed online, without having to leave the comfort of my home, matter of fact I never had to leave my home to complete any portion of the process.  Chris was there every step of the way, following up via email, text and or telephone.  We probably spoke more via text than any other communication means, which I preferred.  If it wasn‚Äôt for the VA taking its time we probably would have had the entire process completed within 30 days, however the government being the government it took a little longer (approximately 60 days from application submittal to closing).

The time we had schedule for closing was right around Christmas and New Years, and we didn‚Äôt plan on being in town during this time and would be out of the state visiting family.  I thought this would put a delay in our process but Chris and his company scheduled a Notary to come to the location where we were vacationing to sign our documents.  However, we were unable to close while on vacation due to the aforementioned delays at the VA.  So we closed within the comforts of our home two days after returning for vacation, we got a great rate, I think we pay about $325 less a month, we pay pretty much the same amount to principle and the balance on the loan only went up about $3500.  I would recommend Chris to anyone of my friends looking to refinance or looking to acquire a mortgage for a new purchase.  When we are looking for our new home in the next year or so, we will definitely be contacting Chris for assistance with another mortgage.</Text>
